reviews.text: Cozy fine dining scene in the city, and inside my favorite hotel! Excellent service and food!

Very amazing French fine dining cooked by Japanese food ingredients.  The chef is famous from one of the Michelin Star restaurant. Must reserve previously as the seasonal full set menu will be well prepared and clients don't need to order the dishes.  Locates at Central in HK, 2/F of The Pottinger Hotel, worth to try!

Such a pleasant experience - it has been a while I sat down for over 4 hours to enjoy a great dinner. The chef was very attentive to my diet and I am impressed by the balance of flavors. Absolutely sublime service!

One of the best fusion restaurant in town!
Yummy and innovative with good services
The chefs are so attentive and added personal touch. The taste - absolutely perfect. Had the same dessert twice, superb taste. Best fine dine ever !

result.name: The Pottinger Hong Kong

reviews.text: Fantastic hotel! The rooms are very nice with excellent ambiance. The dining is great—especially the breakfast. Great location close to public transportation. Highly recommend!

We normally stay at the Salisbury but The Pottinger was recommended and the price was a bit better and included breakfast. We were upgraded to room 610 which was quite good, not large but adequate. The decor in the room and throughout is great too.
Great service, free everyday issue of scmp, bottled water, coffee capsule and tea WG tea bags. Cleaning is meticulous.
Good value. Great location very nice rooms and bar

Lovely hotel. Nice room, friendly front desk, helpful housekeeping (even with language barrier). Nice, big shower room. Good location too, easy to walk to Soho for dinner. Couple of wine shops on the same street. We bought 2 bottles instead of going to a busy and warm night in Lan Kwai Fong. Usual modern amenities in the room. Our TV did not work though, but i didn't really try that hard (nor did I bother to ask for help), maybe i was just using the wrong remote. Anyway, i didnt mind. Best to take the elevated walkways from IFC Hong Kong station than taking a cab. The cab has to go around a long way to get to Stanley street, it set us back HKD50+.
